# Observability

Nocturne is instrumented with [OpenTelemetry](https://opentelemetry.io). When you
point it at an OTLP endpoint, the API and web containers export telemetry to a
collector or observability backend of your choice. With no endpoint set,
telemetry is collected in-process and discarded with negligible overhead, so
there is nothing to disable on a default install.

## What Nocturne emits

| Container | Signals | Source |
|-----------|---------|--------|
| **API** | Metrics, traces, and logs | ASP.NET Core, HTTP client, and .NET runtime instrumentation via Aspire ServiceDefaults |
| **Web** | Server-side traces and logs, plus client-error spans | Node auto-instrumentation (server-side HTTP) and a browser error handler that reports unhandled errors |

Telemetry is **push-based over OTLP**. Nocturne does **not** expose a Prometheus
`/metrics` scrape endpoint -- see **Using Prometheus and Grafana** below if that
is your stack.

<Callout type="info" title="You provide the backend">
  Nocturne does not bundle a collector or a metrics store. You point it at an
  OTLP endpoint you already run (an OpenTelemetry Collector, or a SaaS backend
  such as Grafana Cloud, Honeycomb, Dash0, etc.).
</Callout>

## The single switch

Both containers enable their exporters only when `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT`
is set. Setting it on a container turns telemetry on; leaving it unset keeps it
off. The standard OpenTelemetry SDK environment variables apply:

| Variable | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` | Collector URL. Turns the exporter on. e.g. `http://otel-collector:4317` |
| `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_PROTOCOL` | `grpc` (default, port 4317) or `http/protobuf` (port 4318) |
| `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME` | Service name shown in your backend (e.g. `nocturne-api`, `nocturne-web`) |
| `OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES` | Extra resource attributes, e.g. `deployment.environment=production` |
| `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_HEADERS` | Auth headers for SaaS collectors, e.g. `x-api-key=...` |

## Docker Compose

Both the `nocturne-api` and `nocturne-web` services already reference
`OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` and `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_PROTOCOL` from your `.env`.
Telemetry is off because the endpoint ships empty -- there is no need to edit
the Compose file. To turn it on, set the endpoint in `.env`:

```bash
# .env
OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT=http://otel-collector:4317
OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_PROTOCOL=grpc   # grpc (4317) or http/protobuf (4318)
```

`OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_PROTOCOL` defaults to `grpc` so the API and web containers
agree; change it to `http/protobuf` if your collector expects HTTP (port 4318).
Run the collector as another service on the same Compose network (or point the
endpoint at an external host), then recreate the containers:

```
docker compose up -d
```

<Callout type="tip" title="Only instrument what you need">
  Both services read the same two variables. If you only want backend telemetry,
  override <code>OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT</code> to empty for
  <code>nocturne-web</code> in the Compose file. Otherwise the single
  <code>.env</code> endpoint enables both.
</Callout>

## Kubernetes (Helm)

The Helm chart wires both containers from one `observability.otlp` block. A
single `enabled: true` lights up the API and the web app:

```yaml
observability:
  otlp:
    enabled: true
    endpoint: http://otel-collector.observability.svc.cluster.local:4317
    protocol: grpc
    resourceAttributes:
      deployment.environment: production
    # For collectors that require auth, reference a Secret holding the headers:
    headersSecretRef:
      name: nocturne-otel-headers
      key: headers
```

For a SaaS collector, create the headers Secret first:

```
kubectl create secret generic nocturne-otel-headers \
  --from-literal=headers='x-api-key=...'
```

The chart automatically sets `service.name` (`<release>-nocturne-api` and
`<release>-nocturne-web`), `service.version` (image tag), and
`k8s.namespace.name` / `k8s.pod.name` via the downward API. See the
[chart README](https://github.com/nightscout/nocturne/tree/main/deploy/helm/nocturne)
for the full values reference.

## Using Prometheus and Grafana

Because Nocturne pushes OTLP and has no scrape endpoint, a Prometheus-only setup
needs a bridge. Run an [OpenTelemetry Collector](https://opentelemetry.io/docs/collector/)
with an `otlp` receiver and a `prometheus` (scrape target) or
`prometheusremotewrite` exporter, then point Nocturne at the collector exactly
as above. The collector converts the pushed metrics into something Prometheus
can scrape or receive.

## Privacy: telemetry can contain identifiers

<Callout type="danger" title="Review telemetry before sending it off-site">
  Request URLs and client-error reports can include tenant subdomains and
  identifiers, and traces may carry request metadata. Telemetry only leaves your
  instance once you set <code>OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT</code>. If you send it
  to a third-party backend, treat it as sensitive: prefer a collector you
  control, and use the collector's processors (e.g. attribute/redaction
  processors) to scrub or drop anything you do not want to retain.
</Callout>

## Verifying it works

1. Set the endpoint and restart (Compose) or upgrade the release (Helm).
2. Generate some traffic by opening your instance and signing in.
3. In your backend, look for services named `nocturne-api` and `nocturne-web`
   (or your overridden `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME`) and confirm traces and metrics are
   arriving.
4. If nothing shows up, check the collector is reachable from the containers and
   that the protocol/port match (`grpc` -> 4317, `http/protobuf` -> 4318).
